<br>
Keana,<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> Why is teaming such a big issue?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Read my response to Jeshter or Riggorre above – the reason no teaming was allowed, and the argument is as old as the RTA rotations themselves when initially put forth by Aegirson with nice charts and graphs.  Basically, you have two guilds taking their normal share of the loot pie of the server (one shot rotation per cycle), but then taking a share jointly they couldn’t beat on their own.  So large guilds argue they are taken advantage of, because they are.  If NB can do Statue with 2 groups, and I have 130 people in my guild, shouldn’t I get 10 “shares” of Statue turns to be representative?  A guild that has 36 people, can also kill Statue with 12 people, and they get three “shares” of Statue turns.  Now per capita loot is even and fair to all.  The same number of people get the same amount of loot to split.  To make the system more workable, we tell people they get one shot per guild (2 spots, rather than 15), regardless of size, so that both guilds see the content just as often, even if the loot per capita is skewed in favor of the smaller guild.  Normally the balancing aspect of this, is that I will be able to kill encounters the 36 member guild cannot, and thus get access to loot they can’t, which offsets my “loss” of Statue loot.  Where it becomes a problem, is three 36 member guilds gather together and tackle King Tormax, which none of them could do alone.  Now they get one share of King Tormax loot, and three parts Statue loot.  The argument remains the same for zone flags, just find/replace the word loot with zone flags.  That is how our system dealt with Equal Representation versus Equal Frequency.  That principle of that agreement is breached by teaming on PoP mobs.  <br>
<br>
(Disclaimer: I use Statue and King Tormax as examples only, and are not indicative of skill required to take down, except in their strength relative to each other.  Not available in all states, some restrictions apply, see your dealer for details).<br>
<br>
<br>
Ean,<br>
