<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>I think everyone is starting to see through all the bs, to what this is really about. The top tier pulling the strings, and not wanting to share. Who the hell are you, or anyone else to tell us how to progress through EQ? We'll make our own way through things, how we see fit. &quot;You can't go to so and so zone, if you haven't farmed these items for this many people.&quot; Whatever, the game's versatile, there are usually more than a single way to do things.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
All we want is a level playing field.  To be blunt, IF it was at all about not sharing, we would simply kill all the content that your guild could do, except it would take maybe 2 to 3 groups of us to do it, whenever we wanted.  All we want is our fair share, that's why there are rotations.  Having rotations on mobs makes sure that if you can kill a mob, you can get a fair shot at it, all you gotta do is kill it once.  In fact, this rotation &quot;business&quot; has even caused guilds to be known to ask other guilds who are on a rotation if they can have a shot at the mob and the rotation-guild actually giving the go-ahead for it.  Check on other servers to see how often that happens for them.<br>
<br>
Of course rules are in place to protect each group's &quot;rights&quot; (I hate that word in this game) to mobs.  The &quot;ubers&quot;, as you put it, agree to not spawn camp mobs if you prove that you can kill it.  You get a shot at it too.  In return (remember, compromise is the basis for almost all agreements), up-and-coming guilds agree to &quot;play fair&quot; by not ganging up on mobs.  Were it not for that compromise, the &quot;ubers&quot; would still be farming Vindicator/Statue bps for their 24th twink on late night raids with 12 people and most folks would *still* not have ever enjoyed those encounters.  Were it not for that compromise, all the up-and-coming guilds would have already combined forces into a huge Battle of Helm's End on every mob and chocked them to death with their corpses.  Compromise - you give a little to get a little.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>The funny thing is, since getting our flags, I haven't seen anyone from VoLS in HOH hardly at all. I think that most of us noob guilds are fed up with you telling us what to do, that we amount to nothing, that we zerg, and train, and stink up your space. Just go ahead and keep bending the rules to better suit your needs. <br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I haven't seen an instance of rule bending.  As far as I have seen, the rules in place and discussed are the same that have been agreed upon for more than 2 years.  Please post when/where this rule bending has happened.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>But be careful, one day you are gonna push to hard, and the whole rta thing will fall apart, because who are you to stop 2 mid range guilds from teaming up, and killing any rot mob they see up? You can't actually, because SOE doesn't enforce our little 'civil' game of Wait Your Turn.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Actually, you may be surprised.  SOE does not officially enforce player made agreements.  HOWEVER, cause a stink and see what they do - believe me, I've seen it.  Rathe has always been a server that the GMs brag about because of the low maintenance because the players have a set up government that they all agree to and make work.  Being the Rathe GM was a plumb job - all you had to deal with was the occasional KS, or scam, or someone losing an item - not guilds basically going to war and training/KSing/etc each other night after night.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE FONT START--><span style="color:teal;font-size:medium;">We have always had open discussion and, other than a few folks who simply don't like rotations, most see the wisdom in rotations and agree to them.  IF you have issues, I suggest you do like we have always done.  Call a meeting, meet someone that is accessible by everyone with minimal effort and is safe (not in the middle of ToVN, for instance, but it has been known to happen there) and has little/no /ooc, /auction, /shout spam.  Provide an agenda of what you want to discuss (hopefully some pre-discussion in the agenda to get things rolling before the actual meeting) and sit down and hammer the issues out.  Ask all the involved, or soon to be involved, guilds to send a representative or two.  Then... be civil.  Discuss things.  Be an ass and people will become defensive.  You'd be surprised at what you can work out.  You may even want to discuss the PoFear/PoHate/etc 40-man rule issues as well.</span><!--EZCODE FONT END--><br>
<br>
Interestingly enough, I have yet to see anyone ask for such a meeting.  You all are content to sit on this board and flame each other and spew threats.<br>
<br>
